      <div xml:id="NA163-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu varaivu malintu colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what was said rejoicing in marriage.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA163">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            uyirttaṉa vākuka vaḷiya nāḷu</l>
<l>            mayirttukaṇ mukanta vāṉā vūtaiyō</l>
<l>            ṭelliyu miravu meṉṉātu kalleṉak</l>
<l>            kaṟaṅkicai yiṉamaṇik kaipuṇarn tolippa</l>
<l>            nilavuttavaḻ maṇaṟkō ṭēṟic celvara </l>
<l>            viṉṟe ṉeñcam pōlat toṉṟunaṉi</l>
<l>            varuntuma ṉaḷiya tāmē peruṅkaṭa</l>
<l>            ṉīṉiṟap puṉṉait tamiyoṇ kaitai</l>
<l>            vāṉa mūḻkiya vayaṅkoḷi neṭuñcuṭark</l>
<l>            katirkāyn teḻuntakaṅ kaṉali ñāyiṟṟu </l>
<l>            vaikuṟu vaṉappiṟ ṟōṉṟuṅ</l>
<l>            kaitaiyaṅ kāṉaṟ ṟuṟaivaṉ māvē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>They breathed [hard]. Let them be [well], the pitiable ones, daily,</l>
<l rend="indent2">much [and] of old(?), just as my heart today,</l>
<l rend="indent">while going [and] coming, mounting the sand peaks covered with</l>
<l rend="indent4">moonlight,</l>
<l rend="indent">while the various bells are sounding musically(?)<note place="foot">We have a row of three words for sound in this line (<term xml:lang="ta">kaṟaṅku icai</term> ... <term xml:lang="ta">olippa</term>), and, on top of it, the ideophone <term xml:lang="ta">kalleṉa</term>, the precise connotation of neither of which is properly understood.</note>, combined by hand<note place="foot">What is the meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">kai puṇarntu</term>? United with the hands = fastened?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">noisily, without telling day from night,</l>
<l rend="indent3">with unending cold wind drawing fine sand [and] dust.</l>
<l>They are indeed toiling<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">varuntu</term> here certainly refers just to physical toil and not to mental pain, but just like <term xml:lang="ta">aḷi</term> it is nevertheless employed to evoke the associations of the pains of love in this poem of the incorporation type.</note>,pitiful they,</l>
<l>– the horses of the man from the ghat by the Kaitai grove,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the solitary bright Kaitai tree among the blue-coloured Puṉṉai trees</l>
<l rend="indent">by the great sea(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">peruṅ kaṭal nīl niṟam puṉṉai</term>: here we are faced with the option of either altering the word order (which would be metrically possible) and read <term xml:lang="ta">nīl niṟam peruṅ kaṭal</term>, a quite frequent formulaic description of the sea, or to take <term xml:lang="ta">nīl</term> in the loose sense of dark to actually refer to the Puṉṉai trees.</note> appears like the dawn beauty</l>
<l rend="indent2">of the sun, fiery inside, rising [and] growing hot with rays</l>
<l rend="indent2">of long glow, glowing brightness in which the sky is submerged.<note place="foot">This long description of the rising sun (T.V.G. for one affirms that it is the setting sun, but <term xml:lang="ta">vaikuṟu</term> clearly points to morning) is again nearly unmarked and seems to abound in quasi-synonyms.</note></l>
        </lg>
